@node Setting face attributes
@section Setting face attributes

@findex faces-extras-set-face-attribute
@findex faces-extras-set-face-attributes
@findex faces-extras-set-and-store-face-attributes
@findex faces-extras-set-custom-face-attributes
The package provides a layered system for applying face attributes. At the lowest level, @code{faces-extras-set-face-attribute} takes a single attribute specification---a list whose @code{car} is the face symbol and whose @code{cdr} is a property list of attribute-value pairs---and applies it via @code{set-face-attribute}. Crucially, it evaluates any symbols or functions in the value positions before applying them, so you can use variable names or lambdas as attribute values:

@lisp
(faces-extras-set-face-attribute '(default :height faces-extras-fixed-pitch-size))
@end lisp

The function @code{faces-extras-set-face-attributes} takes a list of such specifications and applies them all.

For persistent management, @code{faces-extras-set-and-store-face-attributes} both applies the attributes immediately and appends them to the variable @code{faces-extras-custom-face-attributes}. List-valued attributes are automatically wrapped in lambdas for deferred evaluation. This means you can accumulate face settings from different parts of your configuration and reapply them all at once.

The command @code{faces-extras-set-custom-face-attributes} reapplies all stored attributes from @code{faces-extras-custom-face-attributes}. This is useful after a theme change or frame creation, when faces may have been reset. You can add it to a theme-loading hook:

@lisp
(add-hook 'modus-themes-after-load-theme-hook
          #'faces-extras-set-custom-face-attributes)
@end lisp

@node Describing faces
@section Describing faces

@findex faces-extras-describe-face
The built-in @code{describe-face} command can be misleading when @code{hl-line-mode} is active, because the highlight overlay adds attributes that obscure the face you are trying to inspect. The command @code{faces-extras-describe-face} temporarily disables both buffer-local @code{hl-line-mode} and @code{global-hl-line-mode}, calls @code{describe-face} with the face at point, and then restores the original mode state. This gives you an accurate reading of the face without manual toggling.

